article.headline: Ford's 21 points, 22 boards career highs
article.linkText: Ford's career day leads Shock over Silver Stars
article.story:
SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- With a double-double at the break and her
team safely ahead, Cheryl Ford could have relaxed in the second
half of the Detroit Shock's first game as defending WNBA champions.

But Ford kept pushing and when the game was over she had career
highs with 21 points and 22 rebounds in the Shock's 73-60 win over
the San Antonio Silver Stars on Saturday night.

"I don't care what league you're in -- that's a great stat
line," Detroit coach Bill Laimbeer said. "Cheryl was a monster
out there."

Ford, a second-year player, said a lot of her success was being
in the right place at the right time.

"I was blocking out and getting the tip-outs," she said.
"That's my job. I go out there and grab rebounds."

Detroit built up a double-digit lead early in the second half
before San Antonio made a late run.

A 3-pointer by Agnieszka Bibrzycka pulled the Silver Stars to
60-56 with about five minutes remaining, but a baseline jumper by
Ruth Riley and a pair of layups by Swin Cash started a 13-4 run
that helped the Shock pull away for good.

"They are some big girls, they're tough," said San Antonio's
Adrienne Goodson, who was scoreless on six shots. "We've got to
get a lot tougher mentally. The same way they came at us, we've got
to come at them."

Cash finished with 14 points, 12 in the second half, and Deanna
Nolan scored 13 and had a career-high nine assists for Detroit.

Shannon Johnson led San Antonio with 16 points in her first game
for the Silver Stars, while Marie Ferdinand scored 14 and Bibrzycka
had 13.

Ford, in her second year in the league, had 13 points and 10
rebounds in the first half.

She set a WNBA record with 12 offensive rebounds. Her previous
career marks were 20 points and 21 rebounds.

The Shock had 21 offensive boards in the game, which helped them
outscore San Antonio 24-10 on second-chance points.

Detroit opened the game by missing eight of its first nine shots
as the Silver Stars took an 8-3 lead.

But the Shock made 12 of their next 20 attempts and led 35-30 at
the break.

San Antonio had the slow start in the second half, missing its
first 10 shots before a turnaround jumper by Margo Dydek with 13:25
left in the game.
